npcs.name: Harriet Tubman
dialog: Got a lot of bundles of wood headed up this way. Are you a friend of the flying bondsmen?%Yes, I am!|What are you talking about?
Well I've got some parcel headed to the Freedom Train. Maybe you could help out sometime?|Never mind. Just an old woman rambling...
#test()|#startEscapeGame()

npcs.name: Newspaper
dialog: SEPTEMBER 1850, CONGRESS REACHES A GREAT COMPROMISE LED BY HENRY CLAY AND STEPHEN DOUGLAS
Congress admits CALIFORNIA into the Union as a FREE STATE.
Both the territories of UTAH and NEW MEXICO are organized now under rule of POPULAR SOVEREIGNTY.
And a harsher FUGITIVE SLAVE ACT has been passed in Congress.
This is already being claimed as greatest compromise since the MISSOURI COMPROMISE OF 1820.

npcs.name: Female Villager
dialog: Can I help you, sir?%I think you are a friend of HARRIET TUBMAN!|Nope!
ME? A friend of the most famous UNDERGROUND RAILROAD CONDUCTOR?|Okay...
That's a very big claim! (and one that can get me in some trouble...)|#END
(hmmmm how can I find out whether I can trust him)
(I know! I can test him! Good thinking, Susan!)
Alright, let me make sure you're a true ABOLITIONIST, want to take my test?%Yes!|No!
Excellent!|Oh...okay then.
(Hmmm....question one, question one...)|#END
Who is the editor for THE LIBERATOR?%William Lloyd Garrison|Jefferson Davis
Too easy! Even a SECESSIONIST would know that one!|WRONG! Come back when you're a true ABOLITIONIST.
(Hmmm...question two, question two...)|#END
Alright! What is the name of HARRIET BEECHER STOWE'S book?%A Tale of Two Cities|Uncle Tom's Cabin
So very wrong! Try reading an ABOLITIONIST book next time!|Uncle Tom's Cabin is correct! (lucky guess...)
#END|(Alright...question three, question three, final question, gotta stump him...)
AHA! The MISSOURI COMPROMISE 30 years ago added what state to OUR SIDE of the Union. The FREE Side!%Missouri|Maine
If that's your side of the Union, than you might as well be a SECESSIONIST!|You're right! Maine is the free state that was added!
Missouri is a SLAVE STATE!|I'm sorry for doubting you, you have to be very cautious in the South.
#END|Ever since the FUGITIVE SLAVE ACT, any one who helps out an escaped slave can be fined!
Worse, the slave will be dragged back to their master's plantation.
Even if they were in a free state!
The only safe place now for slaves is out of the country!
Here! Take these clothes.  Hopefully you are able to get up North!
Safe travels, and remember, if anyone needs a STATIONMASTER, me and my husband are here to serve!

npcs.name: Female Villager
dialog: There's been word that a UNDERGROUND RAILROAD STATIONMASTER was caught just a few miles left of here.
Serves him right for trying to shuffle slaves up North.
Or was it a woman? Either way, shame on him!
...Or her!

npcs.name: Female Villager
dialog: I'm reading this book by HARRIET BEECHER STOWE.  Have you heard of it?%Yes!|What book?
Oh, so you've read it too?|It's this book called UNCLE TOM'S CABIN.
Apparently a lot of folks love this up North.
I'm no ABOLITIONIST, but I can't help to feel put off by some of the things in here...

npcs.name: Male Villager
dialog: Pssst! You there. You wouldn't happen to know if the CONDUCTOR is in town, would you?%Maybe I do|Nope
Aha! A fellow ABOLITIONIST!|My mistake...I thought you were a fighter for freedom...
You see? Not all Southerners are slaveholders.|#END
Make sure you have this map.  It will help you plan your route.
Also, talk to my wife! She can get you clothes.
She is very cautious though, so make sure you answer her questions right!

npcs.name: Male Villager
dialog: Did you hear? Congress just passed a series of bills in a huge COMPROMISE.
HENRY CLAY and STEPHEN DOUGLAS helped write it.
I read about them in that newspaper over there.

npcs.name: Male Villager
dialog: I'm not sure how I feel about the COMPROMISE of 1850.
I like how the North and South were able to find a way to settle issues...
But I'm afraid it will only last for so long...
I mean, sure, a compromise was reached today.
But what if a compromise can't be reached in the future?
What will happen to this young country?

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: Can I do something for you, sir?%Are you looking to get on the RAILROAD?|Nope.
Are you a CONDUCTOR? Oh thank the Lord!|Okay then...
Ever since the FUGITIVE SLAVE ACT was passed, I thought I would never be able to safely get up North.|#END

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: Are you the CONDUCTOR?%Yes I am!|No
Excellent! I am ready to go whenever!|Oh...forget I said anything.

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: I'm ready to get on the RAILROAD whenever you are, sir!

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: I'm ready to go whenever HARRIET TUBMAN is, sir!

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: I heard you are shuffling slaves up North...%Indeed, I am|Who me?
Excellent. I have my stuff packed! Just give me the word when we're leaving.|Oh, my mistake then sir.

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: Rumors are that the lady over there is helping runaway slaves get out of the country.
I think that's a fine and brave deed, but there's no way I want to get too associated with that.
The new FUGITIVE SLAVE ACT is too frightening for me to try and leave.
I do have supplies for the runaways hidden under a tree here.
I just wish I remember which tree it was...

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: I hear you're helping my friends on the UNDERGROUND RAILROAD
They'll need food if they're going to survive...Take this!

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: Although the STATIONMASTERS on the UNDERGROUND RAILROAD will have food, it's better to be safe than sorry.
Please, take this with you!

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: I have been able to sneak in some literature using some underground networks.
I am a huge fan of WILLIAM LLOYD GARRISON'S THE LIBERATOR.  I feel like he really understands our plight.
I recently got UNCLE TOM'S CABIN by HARRIET BEECHER STOWE.
I've been reading that to the others at night when the masters are asleep.
Such a beautiful book. I heard even the Queen of England liked it!

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: I've been hearing the masters debate over this new COMPROMISE Congress has passed.
All I know is that things are definitely going to get harder for runaway slaves.

npcs.name: Male Slave
dialog: If I was half as brave as HARRIET TUBMAN, I'd be a CONDUCTOR too!

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: You're doing a wonderful thing for my friends, sir!
Please take this on your journey.

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: I hear you are trying to shuffle some of my friends out of here.
If I were you, don't go to the town directly north of here.
The STATIONMASTER had to move away so there's no place to rest.

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: A lot of southerners these days are ANTI-ABOLITIONIST and some are even SECESSIONISTS.
However, I think a man and his wife on this plantation are actually undercover ABOLITIONISTS.

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: If I talk to you, the master might get mad.

npcs.name: Female Slave
dialog: People are happy about the COMPROMISE, but it's just like the MISSOURI COMPROMISE 30 years ago.
It will make people happy in the North like adding Maine.
And it will make people happy in the South like adding Missouri
But it will only make them happy for a short period of time.
AHA! The canteen is under here!
